1
00:00:36,133 --> 00:00:38,375
- Beautiful! - An ideal family portrait...

2
00:00:38,594 --> 00:00:40,633
Please look into the camera.

3
00:00:40,929 --> 00:00:43,716
Great! How about a smile?

4
00:00:44,099 --> 00:00:48,761
Let's see some happy faces. You too, Mom... Great!

5
00:00:49,062 --> 00:00:52,561
Take care of your hair! There we have it.

6
00:00:52,857 --> 00:00:56,308
- That should be enough, right? - Yes, I think so.

7
00:00:56,610 --> 00:01:00,442
- We're done with the girls. - You were so good!

8
00:01:00,752 --> 00:01:03,587
- Bye! - You were as good as gold...

9
00:01:03,867 --> 00:01:08,161
How about some shots of the parents on the sofa?

10
00:01:08,421 --> 00:01:12,465
Lean forward, you're sliding too far back. That's it!

11
00:01:12,792 --> 00:01:18,296
- I'll try to belittle myself. - Talk to each other.

12
00:01:18,588 --> 00:01:20,877
Marianne, turn your gaze slightly toward us...

13
00:01:21,174 --> 00:01:26,299
Looks like you guys like each other... I see.

14
00:01:26,596 --> 00:01:28,635
Hold that pose! Great...

15
00:01:28,931 --> 00:01:31,173
- That's it. Thank you very much. - Good!

16
00:01:31,476 --> 00:01:34,761
We'll need some portraits later.

17
00:01:35,020 --> 00:01:37,060
So, let's get started, shall we?

18
00:01:37,273 --> 00:01:41,981
To calm nerves, I always start with a standard question.

19
00:01:42,277 --> 00:01:47,318
- I'm not particularly nervous. - Good. The question is:

20
00:01:47,616 --> 00:01:50,984
How would you describe yourself in a few words?

21
00:01:51,285 --> 00:01:55,365
- That's not easy. - Not so difficult, is it?

22
00:01:55,664 --> 00:01:58,700
- I might be misunderstood. - Really?

23
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:02,666
It may sound conceited when I say that I am highly intelligent, youthful,

24
00:02:02,963 --> 00:02:07,708
successful, sensible, sexy and I care about the world we live in.

25
00:02:08,009 --> 00:02:12,884
I'm educated, well-read, and a good mixer. Let's see...

26
00:02:13,181 --> 00:02:17,224
I am even a good friend to people who are worse off than me.

27
00:02:17,518 --> 00:02:22,891
I'm good at sports. I'm a good husband and a good son.

28
00:02:22,916 --> 00:02:25,538
I have no debt and I pay my taxes.

29
00:02:25,742 --> 00:02:29,441
I respect our government no matter what it does.

30
00:02:30,113 --> 00:02:33,149
I love our royal family. I left the established church.

31
00:02:33,449 --> 00:02:35,240
- Should I continue? - Please.

32
00:02:35,534 --> 00:02:40,492
- I'm a great lover. - Maybe we can skip that question.

33
00:02:40,789 --> 00:02:43,624
And you, Marianne?

34
00:02:44,710 --> 00:02:47,247
Well, what can I say?

35
00:02:47,545 --> 00:02:53,298
I am married to Johan and have two daughters…

36
00:02:53,592 --> 00:02:58,669
- That's all I can think of... - Come on, think more carefully.

37
00:03:01,182 --> 00:03:05,891
- I think Johan is terribly nice... - How kind of you.

38
00:03:06,187 --> 00:03:11,691
- We've been married for 10 years. - We just renewed our contract.

39
00:03:11,984 --> 00:03:17,108
Unlike Johan, I lack the ability to see myself in such glowing terms,

40
00:03:17,405 --> 00:03:21,320
but honestly, I'm glad I can live the life I live.

41
00:03:21,618 --> 00:03:25,698
It's a good life, if you know what I mean.

42
00:03:27,457 --> 00:03:29,948
What else? My goodness, that's difficult...

43
00:03:30,251 --> 00:03:35,671
- She has a beautiful figure. - I try to be serious.

44
00:03:36,882 --> 00:03:40,749
- I have two girls, Karin and Eva. - You already said that.

45
00:03:41,052 --> 00:03:45,264
How about some personal information? Let's start with your age.

46
00:03:45,556 --> 00:03:49,554
- I'm 42, but I don't look it. - I'm 35.

47
00:03:49,852 --> 00:03:52,853
We both come from obscenely middle-class families.

48
00:03:53,147 --> 00:03:59,184
- Johan's father is a doctor. - And my mother is the maternal type.

49
00:03:59,486 --> 00:04:01,312
My father is a lawyer.

50
00:04:01,529 --> 00:04:05,064
It was clear from the beginning that I would also become a lawyer.

51
00:04:05,366 --> 00:04:10,572
I am the youngest of seven children. My mother ran a large household.

52
00:04:10,871 --> 00:04:13,955
- These days she's taking it easy. - Oh, is she?

53
00:04:14,249 --> 00:04:19,456
Curiously, we get along with our parents and see each other often.

54
00:04:19,755 --> 00:04:23,965
There were never any significant frictions.

55
00:04:24,259 --> 00:04:27,175
Let's talk about your jobs.

56
00:04:27,512 --> 00:04:30,263
Mine is a bit unusual.

57
00:04:30,556 --> 00:04:34,090
I am an associate professor at the Institute of Psychotechnology.

58
00:04:34,309 --> 00:04:39,184
Family law is my specialty. I am a member of a large law firm.

59
00:04:39,481 --> 00:04:42,896
Most of my work deals with divorce, but the interesting thing is…

60
00:04:43,192 --> 00:04:45,231
Hold this pose!

61
00:04:45,528 --> 00:04:50,439
Take a photo, I want to capture this expression. Good!

62
00:04:51,784 --> 00:04:55,827
- My goodness, I feel so... - It will pass.

63
00:04:56,121 --> 00:05:00,996
- Tell me, how did you meet? - I'll leave that to Johan.

64
00:05:01,292 --> 00:05:06,713
- Lord, that's interesting! - It wasn't love at first sight.

65
00:05:07,006 --> 00:05:13,209
We both had a large circle of friends and often crossed paths.

66
00:05:13,511 --> 00:05:16,714
We were both politically active for several years

67
00:05:17,015 --> 00:05:21,760
and we did quite a lot of amateur theater as students.

68
00:05:22,061 --> 00:05:26,308
Well, I can't say we made a deeper impression on each other.

69
00:05:26,607 --> 00:05:28,564
Marianne thought I was arrogant.

70
00:05:28,817 --> 00:05:32,945
Johan had a rather public affair with a pop singer…

71
00:05:33,238 --> 00:05:37,734
...which gave him a certain image and made him unbearable.

72
00:05:38,034 --> 00:05:39,991
Marianne war 19.

73
00:05:40,286 --> 00:05:43,951
She was married to a fool whose only salvation was a rich father.

74
00:05:44,249 --> 00:05:48,197
He was very nice and I was totally in love with him.

75
00:05:48,502 --> 00:05:52,713
I also got pregnant early in the relationship.

76
00:05:53,006 --> 00:05:56,706
- But how did it happen that... - that we both joined forces?

77
00:05:57,010 --> 00:06:00,378
That was actually Marianne's idea.

78
00:06:00,679 --> 00:06:03,597
My baby died shortly after birth

79
00:06:03,891 --> 00:06:06,975
and my husband and I divorced, much to our mutual relief.

80
00:06:07,269 --> 00:06:11,183
And Johan's singer had given him notice.

81
00:06:11,482 --> 00:06:14,815
We were both a little hurt and lonely,

82
00:06:15,110 --> 00:06:18,525
So I suggested giving it a try.

83
00:06:18,822 --> 00:06:23,732
We weren't in love at all, but we were both depressed.

84
00:06:24,034 --> 00:06:27,569
And then we realized that we understand each other very well

85
00:06:27,872 --> 00:06:31,999
and we really focused on our studies.

86
00:06:32,292 --> 00:06:38,959
We moved in together, a situation that our mothers actually took calmly.

87
00:06:39,257 --> 00:06:42,542
In fact, they became good friends.

88
00:06:43,927 --> 00:06:47,760
We were accepted as Johan and Marianne.

89
00:06:48,056 --> 00:06:50,345
After six months we got married.

90
00:06:50,642 --> 00:06:53,976
- At that point, we were already in love. - Very much so!

91
00:06:54,270 --> 00:06:59,228
- We were considered the ideal couple. - And that's still the case.

92
00:06:59,526 --> 00:07:04,353
- No complications? - We never had any material worries.

93
00:07:04,655 --> 00:07:09,363
We are in good contact with friends and relatives on both sides.

94
00:07:09,659 --> 00:07:13,953
We have good jobs that we enjoy. We're healthy.

95
00:07:14,247 --> 00:07:20,700
And so on, to an almost vulgar extent. Security, order, loyalty...

96
00:07:21,003 --> 00:07:24,621
We are almost indecently lucky.

97
00:07:25,966 --> 00:07:28,836
Of course we have our differences, just like other people.

98
00:07:29,135 --> 00:07:31,175
But we agree on all the important points.

99
00:07:31,471 --> 00:07:34,804
- Do you never argue? - Marianne does.

100
00:07:35,099 --> 00:07:38,931
Johan is very slow to anger, so I run out of steam.

101
00:07:39,228 --> 00:07:42,597
That all sounds wonderful. All of it.

102
00:07:42,898 --> 00:07:46,148
Just last night someone said

103
00:07:46,443 --> 00:07:50,856
that the very absence of problems is a serious problem.

104
00:07:51,156 --> 00:07:55,367
We are well aware that a life like ours can be dangerous.

105
00:07:55,660 --> 00:07:59,907
What do you mean by dangerous?

106
00:08:00,206 --> 00:08:04,749
The world is going to hell. I claim the right to mind my own business.

107
00:08:05,043 --> 00:08:07,082
Live and let live, that is my motto.

108
00:08:07,379 --> 00:08:12,041
It makes me sick to hear about the latest cure-all.

109
00:08:12,342 --> 00:08:16,968
- I disagree with Johan. - So, what's your opinion?

110
00:08:17,263 --> 00:08:23,383
- I believe in compassion. - Please explain.

111
00:08:23,685 --> 00:08:29,853
If people have learned to care for each other in childhood,

112
00:08:30,150 --> 00:08:32,687
the world would be a different place.

113
00:08:32,985 --> 00:08:36,769
Hold this pose! Please look into the camera.

114
00:08:40,701 --> 00:08:42,444
Listen to this:

115
00:08:42,745 --> 00:08:47,738
“Marianne’s eyes, blue like an old folk song, shine from within.”

116
00:08:48,041 --> 00:08:51,706
When asked how she manages to balance work and household,

117
00:08:52,003 --> 00:08:54,494
she smiles with shy joy

118
00:08:54,797 --> 00:09:00,716
"and replies that she and Johan help each other." - "That's true."

119
00:09:01,011 --> 00:09:03,003
“We understand each other,” she says, “

120
00:09:03,305 --> 00:09:06,970
brightens up as Johan sits down next to her on her heirloom sofa.

121
00:09:07,267 --> 00:09:12,723
“He puts a protective arm around her and she snuggles up to him.”

122
00:09:13,022 --> 00:09:16,722
- Hey! - This is the best!

123
00:09:17,026 --> 00:09:21,522
"So I go and notice that they seem pleased with the prospect."

124
00:09:21,822 --> 00:09:25,237
that they can be alone together again.

125
00:09:25,533 --> 00:09:31,287
Two people who have matured: strong, happy and positive.

126
00:09:31,580 --> 00:09:37,204
“People who never forgot to give love a place of honor.”

127
00:09:37,503 --> 00:09:41,749
- We almost died when we read it. - I wanted to file a complaint.

128
00:09:42,048 --> 00:09:45,584
But our mothers and daughters were simply thrilled with the article.

129
00:09:45,886 --> 00:09:49,384
What really bothers me is that it doesn't say anything about my eyes.

130
00:09:49,680 --> 00:09:55,101
- Isn't there a mysterious glow in them? - They're more like dark pools.

131
00:09:55,394 --> 00:10:01,017
- Actually, very sexy. - Katarina has a crush on you.

132
00:10:01,316 --> 00:10:05,859
- Johan, do you want to run away with me? - A change would do Johan good.

133
00:10:06,154 --> 00:10:09,986
He was so good for 10 years and was never unfaithful.

134
00:10:10,283 --> 00:10:13,237
Are you sure?

135
00:10:13,536 --> 00:10:17,403
I believe everything Johan says.

136
00:10:17,706 --> 00:10:22,866
- Did you hear that, Katarina? - Johan is a better liar than you.

137
00:10:23,170 --> 00:10:26,289
- But I have no imagination. - That's it.

138
00:10:26,590 --> 00:10:33,172
- It makes you a better liar. - Peter spices up his stories.

139
00:10:33,470 --> 00:10:35,179
Sometimes I find it really touching.

140
00:10:35,473 --> 00:10:41,475
I read your article in Technical Times. Even I could understand it.

141
00:10:41,770 --> 00:10:46,099
- Actually, Katarina wrote it. - Are you that smart?

142
00:10:46,399 --> 00:10:51,108
I was in Germany and they wanted an article immediately.

143
00:10:51,403 --> 00:10:54,487
So Katarina wrote it and read it to me on the phone.

144
00:10:54,782 --> 00:10:59,693
- But why was your name on it? - That's not discrimination.

145
00:10:59,995 --> 00:11:03,410
- We work together. - That's admirable.

146
00:11:03,706 --> 00:11:06,376
If you knew the details, you wouldn't say that.

147
00:11:06,667 --> 00:11:11,413
Things are getting a bit dicey between us. Cheers, Katarina, my darling!

148
00:11:11,714 --> 00:11:13,043
Silly...

149
00:11:19,138 --> 00:11:24,427
Do you mind if I speak freely with Johan and Marianne?

150
00:11:32,567 --> 00:11:35,935
- What's wrong, Katarina? - Nothing. Nothing at all.

151
00:11:36,236 --> 00:11:39,521
Only Peter can be so damn clumsy sometimes.

152
00:11:40,324 --> 00:11:42,565
Clumsy is the right word...

153
00:11:42,867 --> 00:11:46,651
I pride myself on being clumsy... and resourceful.

154
00:11:46,954 --> 00:11:49,872
The funny thing is that according to Katarina

155
00:11:50,165 --> 00:11:53,998
I'm nothing more than a spineless jellyfish.

156
00:11:54,295 --> 00:11:58,707
- Jellyfish? Now you're talking. - Let's try to have fun.

157
00:11:59,007 --> 00:12:03,467
Exactly, because we must not forget...

158
00:12:03,761 --> 00:12:06,548
I will now give a thank you speech.

159
00:12:06,847 --> 00:12:10,132
In view of the fabulous magazine article

160
00:12:10,435 --> 00:12:16,104
reminds us that we are in a happy home

161
00:12:16,398 --> 00:12:22,566
that we must not pollute ourselves with emotional garbage.

162
00:12:25,072 --> 00:12:26,947
Cheers, Marianne!

163
00:12:27,241 --> 00:12:30,325
Perhaps I don't envy your domestic happiness...

164
00:12:30,619 --> 00:12:35,245
...but I envy your cooking talent.

165
00:12:35,540 --> 00:12:36,785
No, I really mean it.

166
00:12:37,083 --> 00:12:42,326
I wish Katarina would learn to cook like that.

167
00:12:42,630 --> 00:12:45,121
Katarina is a much better cook.

168
00:12:45,425 --> 00:12:50,584
- Peter says I'm poisoning the food. - It's a running joke in our house.

169
00:12:50,888 --> 00:12:56,759
- Right, it's obviously a joke. - One that's seen better days.

170
00:12:57,061 --> 00:13:02,350
So, let's go into the living room and have some coffee.

171
00:13:04,025 --> 00:13:06,101
So, Johan, what should I do?

172
00:13:06,402 --> 00:13:09,569
I've put my foot in it again.

173
00:13:09,863 --> 00:13:12,864
The girls will clear the table.

174
00:13:20,832 --> 00:13:26,170
- This is all damn touching. - And what?

175
00:13:27,380 --> 00:13:29,455
Your marriage.

176
00:13:29,756 --> 00:13:31,381
Johan and Marianne...

177
00:13:31,676 --> 00:13:35,126
It can move a person to tears.

178
00:13:36,888 --> 00:13:40,838
In fact, you'd really like to stick a pin into the beautiful balloon.

179
00:13:41,142 --> 00:13:45,270
- Would you do that too? - Cheers to you both!

180
00:13:47,815 --> 00:13:52,310
- It's been 10 years, right? - We just had our 10th anniversary.

181
00:13:52,610 --> 00:13:56,940
- No skeletons in the closet? - You never know.

182
00:13:57,241 --> 00:14:02,614
- Both Johan and I like to tidy up. - Can you hear that, Katarina?

183
00:14:02,912 --> 00:14:08,155
This is where you and I have been negligent... We never clean up.

184
00:14:10,002 --> 00:14:14,877
But next week I will call Marianne and make an appointment,

185
00:14:15,173 --> 00:14:18,673
so she can begin our divorce.

186
00:14:20,053 --> 00:14:24,180
By the time Peter sobers up, he will have changed his mind.

187
00:14:24,474 --> 00:14:28,340
Then the computer starts running.

188
00:14:28,644 --> 00:14:31,893
"He says, 'I agree to the divorce.'"

189
00:14:32,189 --> 00:14:36,483
“if Katarina gives up her claim to our assets in Switzerland.”

190
00:14:36,777 --> 00:14:41,106
And my answer is: “But it’s my money, I earned it.”

191
00:14:41,406 --> 00:14:44,110
Then Peter will say that he has multiplied it

192
00:14:44,408 --> 00:14:48,240
and I can have the whole factory.

193
00:14:48,537 --> 00:14:52,866
Then I say, that’s nice of you to give me a factory in Italy –

194
00:14:53,167 --> 00:14:56,831
This becomes riskier with every increase in labor costs.

195
00:14:57,128 --> 00:15:01,375
“- But Katarina, I said... – “Take the whole facility in Sweden.”

196
00:15:01,674 --> 00:15:05,209
The apartment, the country house, the boat, the car,

197
00:15:05,511 --> 00:15:09,555
“The stocks and the premium bonds.” Isn’t that nice?”

198
00:15:09,848 --> 00:15:13,928
I get all taxable items!

199
00:15:15,478 --> 00:15:20,721
Excuse me for talking about such trivial things,

200
00:15:21,025 --> 00:15:26,184
but when Peter starts talking about the fortune, I know how drunk he is.

201
00:15:26,489 --> 00:15:31,364
- And the insults aren't far-fetched. - That's what I've been saying all along.

202
00:15:32,076 --> 00:15:36,952
Katarina is a businesswoman, with equal emphasis on both words.

203
00:15:37,248 --> 00:15:40,664
A businessman...

204
00:15:42,253 --> 00:15:45,586
In addition, she is a brilliant artist

205
00:15:45,882 --> 00:15:50,709
and she has an IQ of I don't know what.

206
00:15:51,011 --> 00:15:54,130
She is also attractive.

207
00:15:54,430 --> 00:15:59,638
It is a model example and is wrapped like a gift.

208
00:15:59,936 --> 00:16:04,597
How I ever had any luck with this monster of perfection is a mystery to me.

209
00:16:04,898 --> 00:16:08,481
I really think we should call a taxi and go home now.

210
00:16:08,777 --> 00:16:12,395
This can’t be pleasant for Johan and Marianne…

211
00:16:12,697 --> 00:16:14,239
No... Johan and Marianne?

212
00:16:14,533 --> 00:16:17,948
These are candy figures decorated with red ribbons.

213
00:16:18,244 --> 00:16:20,569
Just like the marzipan pigs of our childhood.

214
00:16:23,958 --> 00:16:27,042
It is good for their morale,

215
00:16:27,336 --> 00:16:32,412
to look into the bottomless abyss of hell.

216
00:16:39,305 --> 00:16:43,634
August Strindberg

217
00:16:43,934 --> 00:16:46,306
once wrote:

218
00:16:46,603 --> 00:16:50,470
“Is there anything more frightening?”

219
00:16:50,774 --> 00:16:55,850
"as a man and a woman who hate each other?"

220
00:16:57,030 --> 00:17:01,073
What do you think? Maybe child abuse is even worse.

221
00:17:01,367 --> 00:17:07,487
But Katarina and I are children.

222
00:17:07,789 --> 00:17:12,996
Deep down, Katarina is a little girl who cries

223
00:17:13,295 --> 00:17:15,832
because she fell down

224
00:17:16,130 --> 00:17:19,499
and no one comforts her.

225
00:17:20,634 --> 00:17:23,635
And I haven't grown up either.

226
00:17:23,929 --> 00:17:29,303
I cry because Katarina can’t love me,

227
00:17:29,600 --> 00:17:33,052
despite my bad behavior.

228
00:17:33,354 --> 00:17:35,761
There is one thing to be thankful for.

229
00:17:36,065 --> 00:17:40,311
That there is nothing more hellish than this.

230
00:17:40,611 --> 00:17:44,394
That's why we are ready for a divorce.

231
00:17:44,698 --> 00:17:47,367
Provided you listen to reason.

232
00:17:47,659 --> 00:17:50,743
Provided that we simultaneously,

233
00:17:51,038 --> 00:17:53,610
in the presence of the other

234
00:17:53,914 --> 00:17:58,541
and sign all papers in front of trustworthy witnesses.

235
00:17:58,836 --> 00:18:02,619
This way, no one can rip off the other.

236
00:18:02,923 --> 00:18:06,707
- We'll call you this week. - We have a great business lawyer.

237
00:18:07,010 --> 00:18:10,593
Borglund can help you with financial arrangements.

238
00:18:10,889 --> 00:18:12,347
What do you say?

239
00:18:12,640 --> 00:18:17,716
Even if we agree on money matters, you will never let me go.

240
00:18:18,020 --> 00:18:19,680
I am convinced of that.

241
00:18:19,980 --> 00:18:26,314
You think you're so damn indispensable, my dear Katarina?

242
